data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for each case:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Count check — gives clearer failure message ("Expected 3, got 5")
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // All-match predicate — no built-in CollectionAssert, but add a message
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Null check
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key MSTest `CollectionAssert` members:**

| Method | Use case |
|--------|----------|
| `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, item)` | Item exists |
| `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` | Same items, same order |
| `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` | Same items, any order |
| `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(collection)` | No nulls |
| `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)` | No duplicates |
| `CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)` | Subset check |

**Why the changes are better:** `Assert.AreEqual` and `Assert.IsNotNull` produce descriptive failure messages automatically (e.g., "Expected: 3, Actual: 0"), whereas `Assert.IsTrue` only says "Expected: True, Actual: False."
